<subSubSection id="C331C195B755FFEBFFF4FBE1FB17F3E8" pageId="18" pageNumber="125" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8B94921EB755FFEBFFF4FBE1FB17F3E8" blockId="18.[92,1302,725,1543]" pageId="18" pageNumber="125">
<emphasis id="B95F4E0CB755FFEBFFF4FBE1FE08F225" bold="true" box="[95,451,1114,1147]" pageId="18" pageNumber="125">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Data Deficient on The IUCN Red List. Almost nothing is known about status, distribution, and threats to the Manzano Mountain Cottontail. It is probably threatened in its small distribution. Only three locations of the Manzano Mountain Cottontail are known: the type locality, eastern slope of the Sandia Mountains at 2590 m where a specimen was found in 1956, and near Sandia Crest at 3550 m where an individual was likely sighted in 1956. The Manzano Mountain Cottontail might be threatened by habitat loss, drought, and wildfire. Research is needed on its population status, distribution, threats, genetics, biology, and ecology, followed by establishment of appropriate management plans and protected areas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C331C195B755FFEBFFCBFA7EFD9DF059" pageId="18" pageNumber="125" type="bibRefCitation_list">
